display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> be a connected scheme, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> a locally free coherent sheaf on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
    Consider the bundle of projective spaces <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X=\mathbb {P}(E)]]></fr:tex> associated to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>, endowed with its well-known invertible sheaf <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_X(1)]]></fr:tex>.
    Then every invertible sheaf <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {L}]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to a sheaf of the form <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^*(\mathscr {L}')\otimes \mathcal {O}_X(n)]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {L}']]></fr:tex> is an invertible sheaf on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is an integer.
    Furthermore, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is uniquely determined, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {L}']]></fr:tex> is determined up to isomorphism.</fr:p>
  
    
